    <h1>Africa Travel Guide</h1>

    <p>
      Africa captivates travelers in a way no other continent can. From the Big Five roaming the open savanna of East Africa to the surreal landscapes of Namibia's Skeleton Coast, from the cosmopolitan energy of Cape Town to the raw wilderness of the Okavango Delta — Africa is a destination of scale, drama, and profound natural beauty. For the culturally curious traveler, it also offers some of the world's most important human stories: ancient civilizations, the legacy of apartheid, the Maasai and other indigenous cultures living alongside one of the planet's last intact megafauna ecosystems.
    </p>
    <p>
      This guide covers the four sub-regions that reward international travelers most richly: South Africa, the Kenya &amp; Tanzania safari corridor, Botswana, and Namibia.
    </p>

    <h2>South Africa</h2>
    <p>
      South Africa is one of the world's most diverse destinations — geographically, culturally, and ecologically. Few countries pack so much into a single itinerary: one of the world's most beautiful cities, a UNESCO-listed coastline, world-class wine country, a compelling national history, and some of the continent's most accessible wildlife viewing.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Cape Town</strong> anchors any South Africa visit. The V&amp;A Waterfront, the cable car ascent to the summit of Table Mountain, the Cape of Good Hope, and the colorful Bo-Kaap neighborhood form the core of a city that consistently ranks among the world's most beautiful. Day trips into the Cape Winelands — Stellenbosch, Franschhoek, Paarl — add extraordinary scenery and food and wine culture to the mix.
    </p>
    <p>
      The <strong>Garden Route</strong> connects the Western Cape to the Eastern Cape through a spectacular stretch of coast, forest, and lagoon. Knysna, Plettenberg Bay, the Tsitsikamma National Park, and Oudtshoorn's ostrich country are the highlights of a drive that rewards those who take their time.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Kruger National Park</strong> is South Africa's — and arguably Africa's — most famous game reserve. The park's sheer size (roughly the size of Wales) and exceptional road network make it uniquely accessible. Two full days of game drives are enough to encounter lion, leopard, elephant, buffalo, and rhino — the Big Five — alongside cheetah, wild dog, giraffe, and zebra. The nearby private reserves (Sabi Sand, Timbavati) offer more exclusive experiences with off-road driving and walking safaris.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Johannesburg and Soweto</strong> provide an essential encounter with modern South African history. The Apartheid Museum is one of the world's most powerful social history museums; the Hector Pieterson Memorial and a walking tour of Soweto with a local guide bring the story of the anti-apartheid movement to life.
    </p>

