    <h2>Kenya &amp; Tanzania Safari</h2>
    <p>
      The safari corridor spanning Kenya and Tanzania is widely regarded as the greatest wildlife experience on earth. The scale of the wildlife, the quality of the light, the openness of the savanna — and the sheer emotional impact of watching a lion pride move across a golden plain — is unlike anything else in the natural world.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Amboseli National Park</strong> in Kenya offers one of Africa's most iconic images: elephant herds moving in the shadow of Mount Kilimanjaro, its snow-capped summit floating above the heat haze. The park is small enough to explore thoroughly in two days and is one of the best in Africa for close-up elephant encounters.
    </p>
    <p>
      The <strong>Masai Mara</strong> is Kenya's most celebrated reserve and the northern extension of the greater Serengeti ecosystem. Between July and October, the Great Migration brings more than 1.5 million wildebeest and zebra across the Mara River in one of nature's most spectacular events. Outside migration season, the Mara is still among the finest game reserves in Africa for year-round predator sightings.
    </p>
    <p>
      Crossing into Tanzania, the <strong>Serengeti</strong> offers vast plains supporting some of the highest densities of wildlife anywhere on the continent. The Ngorongoro Crater — a collapsed volcanic caldera that functions as a natural enclosure — concentrates wildlife in extraordinary numbers, including one of Africa's last stable black rhinoceros populations.
    </p>

