    <h2>Botswana</h2>
    <p>
      Botswana is the gold standard of high-quality, low-impact wildlife travel. The country's commitment to conservation and deliberately low-volume tourism means visitors experience the bush in relative solitude — no traffic jams of minibuses, no crowds at waterholes. The trade-off is cost: Botswana is one of Africa's more expensive safari destinations, but the exclusivity and the quality of the experience consistently justify it for those who can make the investment.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Chobe National Park</strong> has one of Africa's largest elephant populations — estimates run to 130,000 animals — and extraordinary Nile crocodile and hippo concentrations along the Chobe River. Boat safaris on the river are among the best wildlife-watching experiences in Africa.
    </p>
    <p>
      The <strong>Okavango Delta</strong> is the world's largest inland delta: seasonal flood waters from the Angolan highlands spread across the Kalahari to create a labyrinthine network of channels, lagoons, and islands teeming with life. Traditional mokoro (dugout canoe) excursions, guided bush walks, and night game drives are the signature activities. The Delta's remote camps are accessible only by small aircraft, which adds to both the sense of adventure and the exclusivity.
    </p>

