    <h2>Namibia</h2>
    <p>
      Namibia rewards travelers who seek landscapes of epic, otherworldly scale. The country is vast, sparsely populated, and extraordinarily beautiful — a place where the light, the emptiness, and the sheer strangeness of the terrain create an experience unlike anywhere else in Africa.
    </p>
    <p>
      The red sand dunes of <strong>Sossusvlei</strong> are among the tallest in the world, their crests glowing orange and crimson at sunrise and cooling to deep purple at dusk. The ancient dead trees of Deadvlei, standing bleached and skeletal against burnt ochre sand, have become one of the most photographed landscapes on the continent. Reaching the dunes at sunrise — before the heat builds and the light flattens — is one of Africa's great travel experiences.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Etosha National Park</strong> is a flat, pan-dominated ecosystem where waterholes become natural wildlife stages during the dry season. Lion, elephant, cheetah, black and white rhinoceros, and springbok converge at water sources in concentrations that make photography almost effortless. The <strong>Skeleton Coast</strong> — Namibia's cold, fog-shrouded Atlantic shoreline — adds a haunting maritime dimension: Cape fur seal colonies numbering in the hundreds of thousands, and the rusting wrecks of ships lost to the treacherous surf.
    </p>

