    <div class="card">
      <h3>Africa Travel Tips</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Best season for East Africa:</strong> July–October for dry season and Great Migration river crossings; January–March for calving season in the Serengeti.</li>
        <li><strong>Best season for Southern Africa:</strong> May–September (dry season) for South Africa and Botswana; Namibia is year-round but April–October is cooler and drier.</li>
        <li><strong>Vaccinations:</strong> Yellow fever certification is required for entry into some African countries. Malaria prophylaxis is strongly recommended for East Africa and parts of Southern Africa. Consult a travel medicine clinic at least 6–8 weeks before departure.</li>
        <li><strong>What to pack on safari:</strong> Neutral-colored clothing (khaki, olive, tan) is recommended. Avoid blue and black, which attract tsetse flies. Layers are essential as mornings and evenings in the bush can be very cold even in summer.</li>
        <li><strong>Photography:</strong> A telephoto lens (200–400mm) is invaluable on safari. Most game drives allow photography from open vehicles, and experienced guides position vehicles for optimal light.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

